# Security Report on UbiApps Secure Cloud Mobility

# Introduction

The UbiApps technology builds on and extends the foundation technologies defined by the webinos Open Source Project [1]. The core architecture however, in that it build around a web application framework also shares many qualities with the ChromeOS security framework [2] , FirefoxOS architecture [3] , Tizen architecture [4] and the older HP WebOS security framework [5]. In that all of these technologies are in turn dependent on HTML5 technologies [6] attention should also be given to the work of the Open Web Application Security project [7].

The importance of web application frameworks continues to grow. Several features of web applications ensure their increasing importance going forward (and indeed the growing list of dependent technologies above also is evidence of it)

1. 1)Web application typically have lower development and maintenance costs than native applications.
2. 2)Web applications are typically highly portable, meaning that the same application can be used on many device types with little effort
3. 3)Many enterprises already have extensive web application programming skills in house
4. 4)The royalty free and open nature of web application technologies encourages wide ecosystem growth. 

Considerable efforts are being expended in maturing web application technology for broad consumer adoption. To date relatively little attention has been paid to the requirements of the business user, and the use of web application technology in the enterprise context.

The valuable and highly confidential nature of enterprise data means it is subject to a different class of attacker; one who is prepared to invest considerable time and effort to compromise a single device, rather than the larger scale, volume attacks that characterise attacks on consumer technology.

In this document we will review the core technology and UbiApps innovations in the security space and attempt to reconcile them with the typical risks and attacks

# Abuse Case – General Attacks

Almost all operating systems or application execution environments are capable of running applications. Each application poses potential risks in that an application may have intentional but concealed malign intent or sometimes unintentional (and potentially exploitable) negative impact. Over the past 20 years or so, the containment of the inherent risks has manifested principally in the "arms race" between "malware" and antivirus products on the market. We also see evidence of the threat in the recent trend towards constantly updating Oss and applications, patched with "security updates".

The emergence of Web as an application platform brings with it great benefits, but also risks that need to be managed effectively. The web as an application platform will not succeed unless these risks can be contained. The first step towards effective risk containment is an extensive review of the risks and attack vectors that may be employed.

Below we list how "privallaged APIs" may be abused from a technical attack perspective. These scenarios presume a common web architecture, where UI renders through HTML and code is interpreted Javascript. Some of the attacks relate to common protection methods (e.g. domain based permissioning , or certification) can be overcome.

Later we will show how these risks can be mitigated with appropriate policy and security mechanisms.

## Habituation 

Many risk containment strategies rely on user intervention to reduce risk (or abdicate responsibility). The ubiquitous user prompt or more recently the information bar is the most common form of this. There are a number of criticisms that can be levied against this form of containment, but from an attack perspective it is the phenomena of user habituation which can be either actively or passively abused.

Habituation, is psychological terms, is the process of an individual being so overexposed to a particular stimulus that the stimulus no longer produces the appropriate response. If you keep asking "Can I....? Can I....? Can I...?" you will eventually get an unthinking "yes. Yes. Yes." – or "no. No. No." And not the considered response that you were hoping for. This can make prompting strategies specifically and "challenge response" security schemes, in general, somewhat fragile.

From a malware writers perspective, this fundamental human process can be abused actively or passively:

- Passively: where you rely on an existing security framework, through excessive use of user intervention techniques, to have built up the appropriate habits so that the malware is guaranteed to be granted a privileged permission level through reflex response. For example asking for permission to do XXX every time an application is run will result in a user almost always clicking yes.
- Actively: a more devious attack route involves the malware write creating a program which intentionally build up the required habituated response through artificial means. This automated response is then abused at a later time. E.g.

## General DNS vulnerability

The web experience is build upon the DNS framework. DNS is the mechanism by which an user interpretable domain e.g. [www.mydomain.com](http://www.mydomain.com) is resolved to an IP address eg. 123.123.009.002, which allows a computer to connect to it.

It is an unfortunate fact that DNS itself is easily compromised on most commonly deployed infrastructure. These DNS compromises can include:

- Rewriting of localhosts files
- Attack on the client OS stact
- Intercept of the DNS server on the attached router
- Or the most dangerous which is ARPnet spoofing, easily demonstrable on shared public wireless networks or even fixed corporate networks.

We will not detail here the precise nature of these attacks. These are common knowledge in the hacking community. But excepting that is possible, and given that there is incentive that it is likely, let us look at how this vulnerability may then be exploited within a web application framework.

## Dependent Code DNS Vulnerability (DCDV)

There are many real world instances where web applications make extensive use of "referenced dependent code". Where this code is hosted on a different domain.

For example

- -Google analytics
- -JQuery

If we assume the DNS is compromised, then any use of the above code fragments could lead to any code being executed on the web user agent.

For typical web applications, which are relatively well sandboxed, the risk is arguably low and the incentive of the malware developer to attack therefore minimised. As the sandbox is removed, such as with the addition of device APIs then the incentive to attack increases.

## Critical UI DNS Vulnerability (CUDV)

Web applications may point to assets on a remote domain, for example the use of "button images" which are hyperlinked to an action.

Where this graphical asset is a simple illustrative picture the inherent risk of attack is low. If the referred graphical assets is for example a button with "yes" or "no" , then an attack which simply swaps the referred assets can, in the right context, have quite devastating effects.

## Application Identity Domain Vulnerability (AIDV)

To avoid repeatedly asking a user for "permission" some security mechanism will cache or remember a set of privileges which a particular application is granted. We call this domain anchored permission caching. In the web world this privilege is likely to be issued to a particular domain.

Any such policy is implicitly vulnerable to a domain spoofing attack. If the DNS is compromised on a particular network then any application may spoof itself to originate from a domain to which a permission is likely already granted.

## Trojan

One of the simplest attacks is for an application to pretend to one thing but at a certain point in time actually do something else. For example:

- An application masquerading as a safe password store, may periodically send these details to another location where they may be abused
- An application could implement an "improved" address book, but in fact at regular intervals harvest the contact details and use them for spam email lists.
- Or more subtly an application providing mapping function and therefore granted privileged access to users location details could interact with advert servers to increase their targeted effectiveness.

## Root Certificate Compromise

An alternative to granting permission based upon domain of origin is to use certification mechanisms for anchoring trust. Such is the case for many widget implementations.

The underlying trust mechanism has to cryptographically testify to the integrity and the identity of the signed widget. This algorithm must necessarily make use of a root certificate which is held on the end device.

There are two common variants of root certificate implementation

1. 1Root certificate embedded in the host web user agent. In other words the root certificates are distributed with and embedded in the application.
2. 2Root certificates hosted in the core operating system.

The attacks against the two implementations are subtly different. In the application instance the application can be tampered with and this application somehow distributed(e.g. an application update mechanism that runs over unsecured HTTP is vulnerable to a DNS attack, or a spoof application can be distributed). In the platform OS instance then you either encourage a user to run some system command application to install a new root cert, or perhaps you compromise the a device management protocol which allows remote installation of root certs.

Although the attacks differ the impact is the same in that once the root certificate is compromised then applications can be distributed which circumvent the normal checks

## Private Signing Certificate Compromise

A certificate based permission scheme can be compromised at the other end of the signing process. If a malware writer manages to acquire (by hacking or bribery) the private key with which applications or widgets are signed then again the normal security checks are circumvented and the malware writer has the ability to distribute apps that can make arbitrary use of privileged APIs.

## Technical Exploit

All implementations are buggy. Whether this relates to the implementation of the widget runtime of some other component on the device, certain bugs are exploitable allowing unintended code to be run the device.

Buffer overruns are the classic form of exploit, where a perfectly valid API or interface fails to protect itself against an excess of data being written to it. This data, by virtue of the implementation details then can be exercised as runnable code. This essentially means a malware writer that fully understands the nature of the bug can run arbitrary code on a device.

## Cryptographic Vulnerabilities

Occasionally, vulnerabilities can be found on the fundamental , cryptographic techniques upon which identity anchoring or permission mechanisms can be based. This is generally a rare occurrence but has significant and wide reaching impacts. Hence, a robust policy must recognise it as a possibility, and have the necessary counter measure in place.

## Web/Application Spoofing

Very similar to the Trojan attack, in that it is another instance of an application pretending to be one thing, but in fact being another. We distinguish it here as an application spoofing attack is where a piece of malware is piggy backing on the "visual identify" of another well know application with which the end user may have a trust relationship

Phishing attacks fall into this category, where the impact of a phishing attack, which encourages a user to grant API permissions, can be greater than classic web phishing

## Code Injection (XSS) Self Exploit

Code injection exploits are similar to dependent code dns vulnerability exploits in that they lead to "un-permissioned" code running in a privileged state. The difference here is that the code is executed not due to a dns weakness , but due to interpreted code vulnerabilities on the host application.

For example HMTL coding techniques an allow you to rewrite the web page (injecting new code) using DOM APIs and/or use of javascript eval() can lead to arbitrary code execution. Performing and eval on data a user has input into a input field, is a simple example of this type of vunerability.

XSS exploits can be further subdived into, as per Google Jarlsbug definitions [http://jarlsberg.appspot.com/](http://jarlsberg.appspot.com/)

- -User field XSS
- -Reflected XSS
- -Stored XSS
- -File upload XSS

### Assets

In order to identify threats and elaborate on risks and impact we need to define the assets in our system. The assets will be linked to a stakeholder or persona in the system as an aid to the risk analysis.

#### User:

- ··User-data/User-id
- ··Sensitive APIs, chargeable events etc

#### Developer:

- ··Application
- ··Access to service backend

Network operator/device manufacturer:

- ··Device up-time

The device system resources is an asset which can't easily be bound to a single stakeholder since it is in the interest of the user, the network operator and the device manufacturer that it is not used for malicious purposes for example as a node in a botnet.

#### User/network operator/device manufacturer:

- ··System resources



### Threats

When performing attack tree [1] analysis on a system it is essential that we define the goal of the attackers since this defines the root(s) of the attack tree(s).From the assets identified previously we derive the following main threats:

- ··Unauthorized access to user data
- ··Unauthorized access to sensitive APIs
- ··Unauthorized access to applications
- ··Unauthorized use of system resources
- ··Device DoS attack, i.e. attack the Device up-time

When we analyse these threats we focus our analysis on scenarios where the attacker is either on the network or running in the WEB environment.

Attack trees

### Attack tree modeling

Attack tree modelling is a method to systematically identify and document threats countermeasures. We assume that the reader is familiar with attack trees in general, if not an introduction can be fund here: [http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Attack\_tree](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Attack_tree).

Since an attack tree is a rather new tool in the arsenal of the security engineer the formalism around its graphical representation is quite weak. We therefore introduce our own methodology illustrated in the figure below.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

In the figure below the root node of the attack tree represents the goal of our opponent. To reach that goal the attacker can perform either attack 1 or attack 2 or he must combine the two attacks 3 and 4.

Attack 1 is prevented by the single countermeasure 1 while we must introduce two countermeasures, 2 and 3, to prevent attack 2.

In our fictional case attack 3 is the root of an entire sub tree of attacks and countermeasures, which we illustrate by the bold line on that node. The attack tree stemming from attack 3 can then be described in a separate figure.

In the ideal case all the leaf nodes in the attack tree are countermeasures which mean that all the attacks we can identity can and have been addressed.

Our example above is not that fortunate since we can see that we have found no countermeasure against attack 5. Serendipitously attack 5 relies on the attacker being successful with attack 3 and hence it is enough that we prevent attack 3 to have a secure system.
